<h2>Purpose</h2>
<p>
  Prep research for the consumption-path decision
  (<a href="/backlog/812-how-we-apps-straddle-demos-consume-the-9-moved-block-impl-fa/">#812</a>) that gates the
  <a href="/backlog/697-delete-we-s-vendored-blocks-and-repoint-we-imports-build-to/">#697</a> blocks-deletion
  cutover. Once #697 deletes WE's nine vendored block-impl families, the WE artifacts that <strong>compose</strong>
  those families <em>as building blocks</em> — the two exercise apps and the loader→background-task handoff demo —
  have no sanctioned runtime: they can't iframe (a full app isn't one embeddable block), can't
  <code>import '@frontierui/blocks'</code> (the
  <a href="/backlog/707-reconcile-604-s-we-renders-real-fui-blocks-framing-with-the-/">#707</a> boundary; no
  <code>frontierui</code> vite alias), and
  <a href="/backlog/765-relax-the-we-fui-isolation-boundary-for-an-in-document-di-mo/">#765</a>'s in-document mount
  only mounts a <em>rendered</em> FUI thing. One proposed option (#812 option&nbsp;c) was to
  <strong>extend #765's SDK to hand the app composable block <em>classes/factories</em></strong> at runtime. This
  survey asks the decisive prior-art question: <strong>can a UI implementation be consumed by a separately-owned
  host as composable component classes at runtime, across a trust boundary, without that collapsing into a runtime
  import?</strong>
</p>

<h2>The decisive finding — classes cross the boundary; only opaque units survive it</h2>
<p>
  Across every runtime-integration pattern, the dividing line is <strong>class vs. element/mount</strong>.
  Boundary-<em>preserving</em> patterns hand the host an <strong>opaque unit</strong> — a rendered iframe, a custom
  element (the DOM is the contract), or a global render-function whose <em>signature</em> is the contract. The host
  composes <em>around</em> it, never <em>with its internals</em>. Boundary-<em>collapsing</em> patterns hand over the
  <strong>class/module</strong> — and those are runtime imports by another name, with identical trust blast radius.
  A class the host can instantiate, subclass and wire runs <strong>in the host's realm, with the host's privileges,
  sharing the host's dependency graph</strong> — which is exactly what <code>import '@frontierui/blocks'</code>
  produces. The build step is incidental; what defines the boundary is <em>which realm the code runs in</em>.
</p>

<h2>Framework comparison</h2>
