    <tr>
      <td>Webpack 5 Module Federation / Angular Native Federation</td>
      <td>The <strong>real module/class</strong> (<code>import('remote/Button')</code> → live JS object)</td>
      <td><strong>No</strong> — requires negotiated <code>singleton</code> shared deps + compatible semver across
        both builds; positioned for cooperating apps of <em>one</em> owner</td>
      <td>Proves runtime class-federation is real <em>only</em> by re-establishing a shared-runtime contract — i.e.
        the coupling is the boundary collapse</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Import maps + ESM CDN (esm.sh / Skypack)</td>
      <td>A class fetched + evaluated in the host realm</td>
      <td><strong>No</strong> — third-party code gets full DOM access, no SBOM/sandbox; trust-identical to a
        build-time import</td>
      <td>Removing the build step removes nothing about trust</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Web components as the federation unit</td>
      <td>An <strong>HTML element</strong> (<code>document.createElement(type)</code>); shadow DOM scopes style+DOM</td>
      <td><strong>Yes</strong> — but isolates <em>rendering/DOM/CSS</em>, not composition logic; the host can pass
        props + listen for events only</td>
      <td>This is the &ldquo;managed mount&rdquo; model — exactly #765's in-document mount. It cannot give an app block
        classes to wire.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Micro-frontend taxonomy (Geers / Fowler)</td>
      <td>Iframe DOM, custom element, or a global render-function signature</td>
      <td><strong>Yes</strong> — runtime approaches deliberately avoid handing over code artifacts
        (&ldquo;let's not re-introduce all of that coupling at the release stage&rdquo;)</td>
      <td>None of the boundary-preserving runtime patterns hand the host a composable class; the one that does (MF)
        is the <em>coupled</em>, single-org pattern</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Cross-trust SDKs (Stripe Elements, Intercom)</td>
      <td>A <strong>managed iframe mount</strong> served from the vendor's own origin</td>
      <td><strong>Yes</strong> — Stripe Elements mounts per-field iframes; &ldquo;never read by your website&rdquo;
        (handing out a composable card class would <em>expand</em> PCI scope)</td>
      <td>Every real across-trust-boundary SDK refuses to expose composable classes</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
